data.content:
Here are the MSTest `CollectionAssert` and better `Assert` replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);           // no CollectionAssert equivalent; this is fine

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users); // if nulls matter
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in predicate assert; still best option

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);            // gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);                    // clearer intent + better failure message
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent, better message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, item)` — item absent
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` — subset check

> **Note:** MSTest's `CollectionAssert` doesn't support predicate-based checks like "all items match condition," so `Assert.IsTrue(items.All(...))` remains the standard approach there.
